ssume that randomization is complex and determinism is simple, but in general my experience is the opposite - that randomized algorithms tend to be easier to get right and keep working right.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I’m thinking of a case where I had randomized property testing and people freaked out (and later asked me how to implement it), and now where my boss is saying “why don’t we just transfer all these days in order” and doesn’t seem to get the substantial increase in complexity and fragility or substantial decrease in throughput that represents.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I guess I’m asking for war stories or advice here.&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Wed, 29 Sep 2021 12:46:22 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>You either die an MVP or live long enough to build content moderation</title><link>https://mux.com/blog/you-either-die-an-mvp-or-live-long-enough-to-build-content-moderation</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/djyupr/you_either_die_mvp_live_long_enough_build"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Wed, 29 Sep 2021 22:56:25 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>The GIL and its effects on Python multithreading</title><link>https://tenthousandmeters.com/blog/python-behind-the-scenes-13-the-gil-and-its-effects-on-python-multithreading/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/39xxem/gil_its_effects_on_python_multithreading"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Wed, 29 Sep 2021 12:33:09 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>This Article Best Experienced In the App</title><link>https://ethanmarcotte.com/wrote/locus/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/ulgg4s/this_article_best_experienced_app"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Tue, 28 Sep 2021 20:05:15 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>AMB: the Ancient Machine Book format</title><link>http://amb.osdn.io/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/s7m5lp/amb_ancient_machine_book_format"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Wed, 29 Sep 2021 16:33:50 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>Segcache: a memory-efficient and scalable in-memory key-value cache for small objects</title><link>https://www.usenix.org/system/files/nsdi21-yang.pdf</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/jl73tx/segcache_memory_efficient_scalable"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Wed, 29 Sep 2021 12:27:43 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>Self-Parking Car in &lt;500 Lines of Code</title><link>https://trekhleb.dev/blog/2021